oakcurric:unit-3055
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Dance: phenomenal"@en ;
  curric:slug "dance-phenomenal" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit utilises a thematic approach to provide pupils with a platform to apply
  knowledge from other subject areas. This will enable them to develop movement ideas beyond
  those introduced. Open ended tasks encourage and value a range of responses continuing to
  build creativity and teamwork."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds upon previous knowledge and experience of
  action-space-dynamics-relationships and applies them holistically, allowing opportunities to
  refine and develop their choreographic and performance skills. New choreographic and
  performative elements are introduced in line with their maturity to ensure sustained
  challenge. Time and space is made available to focus on detail and precision of execution to
  complement a wider school ethos in preparing for examinations.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3055-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3055-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3055-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3055-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3055-5 ;
  curric:id "3055"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.539746Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-evaluation-analysis-and-reflection ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-performance-and-competition .

oakcurric:unit-3066
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Dance: movie moves"@en ;
  curric:slug "dance-movie-moves" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit utilises a stylistic approach that introduces both a wider movement
  vocabulary and demonstrates the value of dance as an important social construct; crossing
  time, cultures and emphasising relevance as a lifelong activity for positive physical,
  emotional and social health."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds upon pupil knowledge and understanding of dances from
  other times and places to demonstrate its diversity and continuous evolution. By introducing
  a selection of established social dances, pupils are provided with the opportunity to compare
  and contrast, identify personal preference and consider how they might continue to engage in
  such activities into adulthood on a structured or ad hoc basis. It will also provide some
  insight into current dance cultures, deepening their cultural understanding and appreciation.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3066-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3066-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3066-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3066-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3066-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3066-6 ;
  curric:id "3066"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.584612Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-connect-cultural-and-ethical-awareness ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-performance-and-competition .

oakcurric:unit-3781
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Non-examined assessment: basketball practical"@en ;
  curric:slug "non-examined-assessment-basketball-practical" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit provides pupils with the knowledge and opportunity to replicate skills
  in isolation and in performance scenarios in basketball. As a popular team sport offered
  it will cover passing/receiving, dribbling, shooting, marking and defending and decision
  making in both attack and defence."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already know the correct technique and relevant rules for
  basketball from key stage 3 PE. This unit builds upon this by providing the opportunity to
  evaluate technique and practise some observation and analysis skills. Positioned during the
  autumn term of year 10, it will encourage engagement in extracurricular opportunities,
  including local clubs and competitions, which will allow further improvement of performance.
  This unit will help to prepare students for the practical GCSE moderation in Year 11.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3781-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3781-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3781-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3781-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3781-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3781-6 ;
  curric:id "3781"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.654268Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-3077
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Anatomy and physiology: the short and long term effects of exercise"@en ;
  curric:slug "anatomy-and-physiology-the-short-and-long-term-effects-of-exercise" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore the immediate responses our bodies make to cope with the
  effects of exercise as well as the longer term adaptations it makes in response to
  training that enable us to cope better with exercise and improve performance."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have in-depth understanding of the skeletal, muscular,
  cardiovascular and respiratory systems as well as the impact of exercise intensity and
  duration on our ability to work aerobically. After they deepen their understanding of how the
  body responds to training they will move on to better understand how to train to improve
  health, fitness and sporting performance.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3077-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3077-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3077-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3077-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3077-5 ;
  curric:id "3077"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.729627Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-healthy-active-living .

oakcurric:unit-3054
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Gymnastics: technique, body control and constructive feedback in trampolining"@en ;
  curric:slug "gymnastics-technique-body-control-and-constructive-feedback-in-trampolining" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will develop skills in isolation and in combination with other
  techniques as part of a sequence of movements. To demonstrate control, aesthetics and
  fluency pupils will analyse and provide feedback to their peers. Pupils will also learn
  the basics about the axes of rotation."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed their balance, core stability, body
  tension and basic awareness of flight through gymnastics and dance will have also contributed
  to aesthetic awareness and routine creation. Pupils will experiment with and plan their own
  sequences of increasing complexity with simple link moves. Pupils will have the chance to
  further develop their reflective and analytical skills in upcoming units. The intention is
  also to expose pupils to an activity they could pursue beyond the curriculum.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3054-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3054-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3054-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3054-4 ;
  curric:id "3054"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.767276Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-movement-competence ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-evaluation-analysis-and-reflection .

oakcurric:unit-3806
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Health and wellbeing: cardio tennis"@en ;
  curric:slug "health-and-wellbeing-cardio-tennis" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will develop pupils’ understanding of a variety of ways to have fun
  whilst improving personal health and fitness. Their movement skills and cardiovascular
  endurance will improve whilst engaging in tennis based exercises."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed their understanding of what it means to
  commit to a personalised training plan and the different components of fitness that are
  important to them. They will have considered how exercise and nutrition complement each other
  to support a healthy and active lifestyle. Later in health and wellbeing pupils will explore
  a variety of additional approaches to holistic wellbeing to include couch to 5k; yoga,
  pilates and mindfulness; and exercises associated with martial arts and self-defence.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3806-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3806-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3806-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3806-4 ;
  curric:id "3806"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.771076Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-3052
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: tactics and strategies in world games"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-tactics-and-strategies-in-world-games" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores tactics and strategies that can be transferred to a variety of
  world games including Kabaddi, flag and Aussie Rules football (AFL). These popular
  participation and spectator sports from different cultures require pupils to pick up new
  rules and adapt tactics to play as a team."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed ways to adapt skills, tactics and
  strategies from various forms of football and contact sports like rugby. This unit provides
  an opportunity to learn and transfer to other unfamiliar games but also to learn about
  socio-cultural factors that influence game design. Later in invasion games they will apply
  more advanced tactics and strategies in rugby and korfball.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3052-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3052-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3052-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3052-4 ;
  curric:id "3052"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.017171Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-decision-making-problem-solving-and-creative-thinking ,
    oakcurric:thread-move-application-of-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas .

oakcurric:unit-3053
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Invasion games: tactics and strategies in hockey"@en ;
  curric:slug "invasion-games-tactics-and-strategies-in-hockey" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores a variety of tactics and strategies that can be transferred
  from other team games to hockey. Pupils’ persistence will be tested as they learn to apply
  the rules and find ways to tackle safely, strike the ball cleanly and avoid kicking the
  ball."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have developed ways to adapt skills, tactics and
  strategies from various forms of football but this unit places an implement in their hand
  which adds an extra dimension of challenge. This unit provides an opportunity to transfer
  some knowledge and skills from racket sports as well as other field games in terms of
  movement off the ball, creating space and outwitting opponents. Later in invasion games they
  will apply more advanced tactics and strategies.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3053-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3053-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3053-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3053-4 ;
  curric:id "3053"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.108953Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-application-of-tactics-strategies-and-compositional-ideas ,
    oakcurric:thread-feel-personal-and-emotional .

oakcurric:unit-3081
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Physical training: injury and injury prevention"@en ;
  curric:slug "physical-training-injury-and-injury-prevention" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit unpicks the many factors to be considered to prevent injury in sport. It
  focussess on the effective delivery of both warm up and cool down components of training."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will build on basic understanding of injury and injury prevention
  gained through key stage 3 and their involvement in sport and physical activity. From the
  earlier physical training units they will understand which components of fitness are most
  important for different sports. They will appreciate the principles and methods of training
  that are most beneficial for different individuals. Later in physical training they will
  consider performance enhancing drugs and why some athletes are tempted to use them as well as
  gaining an appreciation of the negative side effects of specific drugs.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3081-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3081-2 ;
  curric:id "3081"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.314430Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-move-physical-fitness ,
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-healthy-active-living .

oakcurric:unit-3076
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Anatomy and physiology: anaerobic and aerobic exercise"@en ;
  curric:slug "anatomy-and-physiology-anaerobic-and-aerobic-exercise" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit will explore the impact of varying the intensity and durations of
  exercise upon the build up of lactic acid and recovery rates. Exercises will be classified
  as either aerobic (with sufficient oxygen) or anaerobic (without sufficient oxygen)."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will already have experienced the impact of lactic acid build up on
  their ability to keep exercising. They will know how the muscles require oxygen to provide
  energy for movement and how the cardio-respiratory systems work together to transport that
  oxygen around the body as well as removing the waste product of carbon dioxide. They will
  later go on to unpick the specific short and long term effects of exercise on the body.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3076-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3076-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3076-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3076-4 ;
  curric:id "3076"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.682045Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-knowledge-of-healthy-active-living .

oakcurric:unit-3083
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Use of data"@en ;
  curric:slug "use-of-data" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit supports pupils to be able to demonstrate an understanding of how both
  qualitative and quantitative data are collected, presented and analysed to include tables
  and graphs."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils will further develop their understanding of how data relating to
  physical activity participation or sports performance can be collected, compared to normative
  data and presented to help inform analysis. As a synoptic skill that is required to tackle
  aspects of both paper 1 and paper 2 content this unit will draw on examples from a number of
  topic areas and be further explored in socio-cultural and health, fitness and well-being
  units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3083-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3083-2 ;
  curric:id "3083"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.779278Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-physical-education-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-think-evaluation-analysis-and-reflection .

